[{"id":29730,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["cis-2-butene and trans-2-butene are not interconvertible at room temperature.","cis-2-butene and trans-2-butene are stereoisomers.","cis-2-butene has less dipole moment than trans-2-butene.","trans-2-butene is more stable than cis-2-butene."],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/tF53ZvS1DWE-0ATRgumPMCnCrjCUrdP2wcHcF5GEeFI.original.fullsize.png\"><br />Cis-but-2-ene has higher Dipole moment than trans-but-2-ene.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29821,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Following points are to be remembered when checking for chirality in a compound:<br />1.Compound should have a stereogenic centre.<br />2. Compound shouldn&#39;t have any plane&nbsp;of symmetry as it can convert a chiral compound to a meso compound.<br />Based on the above two facts, out of the following, only 2 are chiral compounds:<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/644e888e-35bc-40dd-b999-de28b6d2e622-9896613_2.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 232px;\" /></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2d8fcef1-56bd-4dab-93ef-2a5bcb4f6533-9896613_3.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 273px;\" /></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5a6b0538-8888-4d80-8129-c25c823b8953-9896613_4.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 286px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29877,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Volume of N<sub>2</sub> gas is equal to 22.4 ml at STP<br />Mole of N<sub>2</sub> gas =&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>22</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow><mn>22400</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>1000</mn></mfrac></math><br />Weight of N<sub>2</sub> gas =<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>1000</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>28</mn></math></p><p>% of N in organic compound&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>28</mn><mn>1000</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mn>100</mn><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p><p>Hence,&nbsp;The percentage of nitrogen in the compound is 14%</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29711,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["I \\(>\\) II \\(>\\) III","II \\(>\\) III \\(>\\) I","II \\(>\\) I \\(>\\) III","III \\(>\\) II \\(>\\) I"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/LDhfuDa0-9dJZMTaapmBDTqRMoiMVnTqr3TF-YjRgIg.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29909,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Moles of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Br</mi><mo>=</mo></math> Moles of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AgBr</mi></math> obtained</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo></math> Mass of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Br</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2397</mn></mrow><mn>188</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>80</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math>&nbsp;</p><p>therefore <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo><mi>Br</mi></math> in the organic compound</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><mi>Br</mi></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2397</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>80</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>188</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>15</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>85</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>80</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>68</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo></math> Nearest integer is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>'</mo><mn>68</mn><mo>'</mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29954,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["fractional distillation, isohexane","simple distillation, <math><mn>3</mn></math> -methylpentane","simple distillation, isohexane","fractional distillation, <math><mn>3</mn></math> -methylpentane"],"answer":0,"solution":"Liquid having lower boiling point comes out first in fractional distillation. fractional distillation is generally used if in boiling point is small.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29833,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Molecular mass of Barium Sulphate(<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BaSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>) =&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>233</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo><mi>sulphur</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>32</mn><mn>233</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mtext>&#160;weight of&#160;</mtext><msub><mi>BaSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mtext>&#160;formed&#160;</mtext></mrow><mtext>&#160;weight of organic compound&#160;</mtext></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>32</mn><mn>233</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4439</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>471</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>42</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>10</mn></math></p><p>Nearest integer:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>42</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29635,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A-II, B-III, C-I, D-IV","A-II, B-IV, C-I, D-III","A-II, B-IV, C-III, D-I","A-IV, B-III, C-II, D-I"],"answer":1,"solution":"Simple distillation is used to separate two liquids with a large difference in boiling points.<br><br>Fractional distillation is used to separate two liquids with close boiling points.<br><br>Steam distillation is used to separate steam volatile compounds.<br><br>Distillation under reduced pressure is used to separate liquids that decompose at their boiling points.<br><br>Therefore, the correct match is A-II, B-IV, C-I, D-III.<br><br>Answer: A-II, B-IV, C-I, D-III","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29929,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>&nbsp;only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>&nbsp;only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>&nbsp;only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>&nbsp;only"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Compounds which are more acidic then <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>,&nbsp;gives <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> gas on reaction with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaHCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>.&nbsp;Compound <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> i.e. Benzoic acid and compound <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>&nbsp;i.e. picric acid both are more acidic than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8b19ac82-5b07-4e33-885d-bef75c91ae56-image.png\" style=\"width: 404px; height: 188px;\" /></p><p>equilibrium favours forward direction and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8593;</mo></math> is liberated.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a36c1468-d58f-4cf3-ad64-d53745bec0f5-image.png\" style=\"width: 468px; height: 202px;\" /></p><p>Equilibrium favours backward&nbsp;direction and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8593;</mo></math> is not liberated.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30026,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{S}$","$\\mathrm{Cl}$","$\\mathrm{C}$ and $\\mathrm{H}$","$\\mathrm{N}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Beilstein's test is used for halogens.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (19 May Online)","image":null},{"id":30074,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1POZbAA2GsSzuTvsfUkskZrzitezjy_g1r1a0PSuhsk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/K8y5Ln2xGCFiNJPZ6ljXdjfZQMXn0b5_N8cAjj1XJcE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/DY4bZJy9Q-tP9p-hbsVYN50c6I2yETgJHWiMOgOFhTk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/k-psFXxDBoc2wh4PSE8L4ivLIgZ6yfOlWRFWsGM44Oc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null},{"id":29968,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"Reactivity of <math><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;substitution<math><mo>&#8733;</mo></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math> can be&nbsp;present on the aromatic compound.<br />Electrophilic substitution <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8733;</mo><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math><mo>&#8733;</mo><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math><mo>&#8733;</mo><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c88c623b-9937-44de-939e-9b02c9102e25-image.png\" style=\"width: 417px; height: 237px;\" /><br />(order of <math><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math> density <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi></math> electrophilic substitution)<br />Ring <math><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math> density is highest.<br />So <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29990,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<p><img height=\"84\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/83832d3f-622d-4fcc-9559-3546901a451e-image.png\" width=\"86\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"71\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/70e14baf-3df4-4080-9cdb-a6e56a4d7320-image.png\" style=\"float: left;\" width=\"89\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><img height=\"72\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2cfc1efa-67ba-405a-859e-a2fdf3629a7e-image.png\" style=\"float: left;\" width=\"84\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><img height=\"75\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/91676807-6a73-4566-a331-d9997d564281-image.png\" style=\"float: left;\" width=\"74\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img height=\"86\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2fa4597b-d455-4df7-82c6-4ea8cbd65dc6-image.png\" width=\"304\" /><br />Since anion is Aromatic, the reactant will have a high affinity for the reaction and hence, will be most reactive.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":29735,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ZQFr5P_7XAcqgqGKNX7639PdpKrB670tOaUFmmPIxoE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/II3w9zJyG7P-k2_CbOINoYCjWl_DDcH4_XWh8xByvyk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/PqD47tB1Y0BSGB0OlMa3wSbI7_34rDxGJGrCd64F9LE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/sk0qPHhOqWb_1J6p6k46KSoQtEFwCZHZ-UdeuHrnUKg.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"Metamer $\\Rightarrow$ Isomer having same molecular formula, same functional group but different alkyl/aryl groups on either side of functional group.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29835,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b88a212a-699b-4eb4-b0d4-908e9bd6d5b9-9893509.PNG\" style=\"width: 320px; height: 333px;\" /></p><p>In the molecule C, positive charge is present on the electronegative oxygen atom and is not having complete octet. Hence, the structure C is the least stable resonance structure. In the structure A, the delocalisation is taken place away from the electron withdrawing group, which is not favourable delocalisation. In the structure D, more number of covalent bonds are there and having all atoms&#39; octet.</p><p>Order should be : <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (24 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29795,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f275999c-09da-4b8f-adc6-d8e39c27ac65.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 144px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/884cd34d-ba72-4e09-b2a1-70bdfa9814b0.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 178px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f2b7744c-a044-4353-8351-c99e7d9e56ad.png\" style=\"width: 110px; height: 198px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/50327148-3f80-44b7-becd-de40b400c140.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 160px;\"/>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>When keto form loses a proton from the alpha carbon, it goes to the enol form. Depending on whether the proton is lost from oxygen or carbon, this conjugate acid can deliver either the carbonyl form or the enol form. </p><p>In this case, after enolisation, it forms an aromatic compound.</p><p>Aromatic compounds are stable due to their aromaticity. The resonance stabilisation resulting from delocalised pi electrons distributes the charge over the entire ring, reducing the overall energy of the compound.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/23feaddd-9466-410a-8ab9-18d88b1bc319.png\" style=\"width: 334px; height: 168px;\"/></p><p>Hence, the answer is option B.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30056,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Cl","$\\mathrm{NH}_2$","$\\mathrm{OC}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5$","OCOR"],"answer":0,"solution":"Conjugated acid of $\\mathrm{Cl}^{-}$is a stronger acid i.e. $\\mathrm{HCl}$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":29736,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["2-formyl-4-hydroxyhept-7-enoic acid","2-formyl-4-hydroxyhept-6-enoic acid","2-carboxy-4-hydroxyhept-7-enal","2-carboxy-4-hydroxyhept-6-enal"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/j9-qijJGRFLe4zBZpKF07avzy0Dq9F0OPu0PoEG6of4.original.fullsize.png\"><br />2-formly-4-hydroxyhept-6-enoic acid","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29697,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Mass of organic compound $=0.25 \\mathrm{~g}$\nMass of $\\mathrm{AgBr}=0.15 \\mathrm{~g}$\nNo. of moles of $\\mathrm{Br}=$ No. of moles of $\\mathrm{AgBr}=\\frac{0.15}{188}$\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\text { Mass of } \\mathrm{Br}=\\frac{0.15 \\times 80}{188} \\mathrm{~g} \\\\\n& \\% \\text { of } \\mathrm{Br}=\\frac{0.15 \\times 80 \\times 100}{188 \\times 0.25} \\\\\n& =25.5 \\% \\\\\n& =255 \\times 10^{-1} \\%\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (24 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29728,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6MaJr7Oc8mHLJKIS-ILqc_LFoHtmLeYj7pkJBr9ev0k.original.fullsize.png\"><br />Total chiral centre $=5$\nNo. of optical isomers $=2^5=32$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29708,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$2$","$1$","$4$","$3$"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/eA4SYTBoi4PzjfGuMcpjoEtpnVl5bs6KPMj6J_9LRp0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\n\n\nIt has 4 stereoisomers $\\left[\\begin{array}{ll}R \\text { cis } & \\mathrm{R} \\text { trans } \\\\ \\mathrm{Scis} & \\text { Strans }\\end{array}\\right]$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29960,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img height=\"128\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f3902acd-9f38-4425-ae7f-870e491484e6-image.png\" width=\"460\" /><br />Reason: Due to most stable carbocatin formation tert-butyl chloride given the ppt immediately.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29873,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Chromatographic separation","Steam&nbsp;distillation","Fractional Crystallisation","Sublimation"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/75b14898-9e4d-4c21-85b7-7f21b0fd9feb-image.png\" style=\"width: 328px; height: 150px;\" /></p><p>The compound <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&nbsp;is&nbsp;steam volatile. It is due to the presence of intramolecular hydrogen bonding in the compound&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>. Hence, the above mixture can be separated by steam distillation.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29678,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["3-Bromo-2-hydroxy-5-nitrobenzoic acid","3-Bromo-4-hydroxy-1-nitrobenzoic acid","2-Hydroxy-3-bromo-5-nitrobenzoic acid","5-Nitro-3-bromo-2-hydroxybenzoic acid"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/_Nion4jDxxaifI8CMq3cwg_AxtPQlKmiH-kqdhAFzBc.original.fullsize.png\"/><br />IUPAC 3-Bromo-2-hydroxy-5-nitro-Benzoic acid","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (3 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29732,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ysbCMO0samtISq4i2_voppsd_VTO59fae7aFjyK5l6g.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29689,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{array}{ll}\\text { Organic Compound } \\longrightarrow & \\mathrm{BaSO}_4 \\\\ 0.20 \\mathrm{gm} & 0.40 \\mathrm{gm} \\\\ & \\frac{0.40}{233} \\mathrm{~mol}\\left(\\mathrm{BaSO}_4\\right) \\\\ & \\frac{0.40}{233} \\mathrm{~mol} \\text { (Sulphur) } \\\\ & \\frac{0.40}{233} \\times 32 \\mathrm{gm} \\text { (sulphur) }\\end{array}$\n\n\n\n$\\% \\mathrm{~S}=\\frac{\\frac{0.40 \\times 32}{233} \\times 100}{0.20}=27.5 \\%$ or $275 \\times 10^{-1} \\%$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30002,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["24","3","5","10"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Total millimoles of sulphuric acid =<math><mn>60</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></math><br /><br />Excess <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub><mo>&#8801;</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></math><br /><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></math> used in reaction with ammonia <math><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math><br /><br />Based on the reaction stoichiometry,&nbsp;<math><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub><mo>&#10230;</mo><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></math></p><p>mm of <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p>Mass of <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>14</mn><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0.140</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math></p><p><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0.140</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>1.4</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":29670,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Statement I is correct but statement II is incorrect","Statement I is incorrect but statement II is correct","Both statement I and statement II are incorrect","Both statement I and statement II are correct"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e08gIEAHPPOOtpke2jqy5kZDfKtoPcoF2ng876RWJWs.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29964,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Higher <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></mrow></msub></math> value means higher adsorption.","The value of  <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></mrow></msub></math>  cannot be more than one.","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></mrow></msub></math> value depends on the type of chromatography.","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></mrow></msub></math> value of dependent on the mobile phase."],"answer":0,"solution":"<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></mrow></msub></math> or Retention factor or Retardation factor <math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br />For low polarity compounds, lower will be adsorption and the lower the value of adsorption higher will be <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></mrow></msub></math> value<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/79022a81-b5ff-40cb-bb49-1c5fd3e7bcfa-image.png\" style=\"width: 260px; height: 197px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29931,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1c521357-fadb-4229-b975-80aefb76b7c0-image.png\" style=\"width: 90px; height: 84px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/df0865a4-9f24-450a-9163-775da87fad58-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 87px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5f3913c8-c0ba-406b-ac6a-5c37a0faca37-image.png\" style=\"width: 100px; height: 98px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7861538d-3ea1-496d-912e-c78f86b8943d-image.png\" style=\"width: 118px; height: 84px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>For the following ion/compounds</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e8fb8e10-64c2-4b24-9dd2-ad638a9edc89-image.png\" style=\"width: 243px; height: 228px;\" /></p><p>The main difference between aromatic antiaromatic and nonaromatic is that aromatic means having a delocalized pi electron system with (4n +2) electrons and antiaromatic means having a delocalized pi electron system with 4 electrons whereas nonaromatic means there is no delocalized electron system in that molecule.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29951,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Basicity is inversely proportional to electronegativity.</p><p>Higher the electron affinity or core charge of an atom, the less likely it is to donate its electrons to a proton.<br />Greater the delocalization of electrons that could potentially donate to a proton, the less able they are to donate.<br />Greater the electron-withdrawing effects in another part of a molecule, the less likely the electrons on a particular atom are to donate.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29991,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>III</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>III</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>III</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>IV</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"The different group should be attached to each <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math> hybridised <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo></math>atom.<br />It has <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> group at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>, so it will not show geometrical&nbsp;isomerism.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":29807,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["B, A, C","B, C, A","A, C, B","C, A, B"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>The process of extraction of different compounds absorbed on the column by means of a suitable solvent (eluent) is called &#39;elution&#39;. Silica gel and solvent methylene chloride both are polar. The polar solvent and silica gel bind the polar compound, so it moves very slowly, whereas the non-polar compound moves faster on the silica gel.</p><p>Correct order of elution <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29966,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Differential adsorption of the substances on the solid phase.","Differential absorption of the substances on the solid phase.","Gravitational force.","Capillary action"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Principal of chromatography is based on adsorption of the substance on the solid phase.</p><p>A Chromatography column is a device used in chromatography for the separation of chemical compounds. A chromatography column contains the stationary phase, allowing the mobile phase to pass through it. Chromatography columns of different types are used in both gas and liquid chromatography.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29921,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>In Duma&#39;s method of estimation of Nitrogen. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1840</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gm</mi></math> of organic compound gave <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>30</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mL</mi></math> of nitrogen which is collected at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>287</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>758</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math> of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Hg</mi></math>.</p><p>Given ;&nbsp;</p><p>Aqueous tension at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>287</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Hg</mi></math>.</p><p>Hence, actual pressure <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>758</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>14</mn></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>744</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>&nbsp;of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Hg</mi></math>.</p><p>Volume of nitrogen at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>STP</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>273</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>744</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>30</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>287</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>760</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>27</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>935</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mL</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8757;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>22400</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mL</mi></math> of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> at STP weighs <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>28</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gm</mi></math>.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>27</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>94</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mL</mi></math> of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>STP</mi></math> weighs <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>28</mn><mn>22400</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>27</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>94</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0349</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gm</mi></math></p><p>Hence&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo></math> of Nitrogen&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0349</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1840</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>18</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>97</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p><p>Round off. Answer <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>19</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (16 Mar Shift 2)","image":null}]